>
  <p>
    Wealth stewardship is the discipline of transferring, preserving, and activating wealth across generations in ways that strengthen rather than diminish the family. It encompasses the technical instruments of estate planning and trust design, but it extends far beyond them — into the psychological, relational, and behavioral dimensions that ultimately determine whether wealth endures.
  </p>

  <p>
    The statistics are well known. Approximately 70% of inherited wealth is dissipated by the second generation, and 90% by the third. What is less frequently discussed is why. The failure is rarely technical. Trust structures are properly drafted. Tax strategies are meticulously executed. Investment portfolios are professionally managed. The failure is human — and it is almost always rooted in the behavioral and psychological dimensions that the traditional wealth advisory framework systematically overlooks.
  </p>

  <h2>Where Behavioral Health Meets Wealth Transfer</h2>

  <p>
    Every significant wealth transfer is, at its core, a behavioral event. The heir who receives a substantial inheritance is not merely receiving assets. They are receiving a set of expectations, a family narrative, an identity challenge, and — in many cases — a psychological burden that they have never been prepared to carry.
  </p>

  <p>
    Research in the psychology of inherited wealth reveals consistent patterns: identity confusion, guilt, difficulty forming authentic relationships, substance use as self-medication, and the paradox of having every material resource available while lacking the internal resources to use them wisely. These are not character failures. They are predictable outcomes of circumstances that most psychological and advisory frameworks were never designed to address.
  </p>

  <p>
    For fiduciaries and wealth advisors, understanding these dynamics is not optional. It is essential to the competent exercise of their duties. A trustee who structures distributions without understanding the psychological impact of inherited wealth is operating with incomplete information. A wealth advisor who prepares a succession plan without addressing the behavioral readiness of heirs is building on an unstable foundation.
  </p>

  <h2>Trust Design as Behavioral Architecture</h2>

  <p>
    The trust document is among the most powerful tools available for influencing behavior across generations. Yet trust design remains overwhelmingly focused on tax optimization and asset protection, with behavioral provisions treated as afterthoughts when they are addressed at all.
  </p>

  <p>
    A well-designed trust can support genuine recovery from substance use disorders, incentivize personal development, accommodate the complexities of behavioral health treatment, and create structures that promote autonomy while maintaining appropriate safeguards. A poorly designed trust can enable destructive behavior, punish vulnerability, and create adversarial dynamics between beneficiaries and trustees that persist for decades.
  </p>

  <p>
    The distinction between these outcomes lies not in the sophistication of the legal drafting but in the depth of understanding brought to the behavioral dimensions of the family's circumstances. The articles in this section explore how trust structures can be designed with behavioral intelligence — serving the long-term wellbeing of beneficiaries rather than merely the technical requirements of wealth preservation.
  </p>

  <h2>The Advisor's Expanding Role</h2>

  <p>
    The wealth advisory profession is in the early stages of a fundamental transformation. The traditional model — in which the advisor manages assets and leaves personal matters to other professionals — is giving way to a more integrated approach in which the advisor understands the behavioral dimensions of wealth and incorporates that understanding into every aspect of their practice.
  </p>

  <p>
    This transformation is being driven by the realities that advisors encounter in their practices. The client whose substance use is eroding the family's financial foundation. The heir whose lack of preparation is evident to everyone except the patriarch who controls the estate plan. The family whose philanthropic aspirations are undermined by behavioral dynamics that no one is willing to name.
  </p>

  <p>
    The articles in this section provide frameworks for advisors who are navigating this transformation — who recognize that their most valuable service is not portfolio optimization but the integration of financial and behavioral intelligence in service of multigenerational family resilience.
  </p>
